{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17470920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17470920"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:42:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"76"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/76"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.04,0.01,0.07,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"76"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92434"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/76"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"76"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75756"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"151"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"6625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31627"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44018"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92434"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-year-old boy is brought to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of lethargy, irritability and pallor. He has a history of several respiratory tract infections this year and gastroenteritis from suspected food poisoning one week ago. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 145/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal anaemia with fragmented erythrocytes on peripheral blood film, thrombocytopenia, and elevated serum creatinine. Coagulation studies are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Immune thrombocytopaenic purpura","Disseminated intravascular coagulation","Malignant hypertension","Henoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura","Haemolytic uraemic syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of haemolytic uraemic syndrome (HUS): microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia (evidenced by fragmented erythrocytes), thrombocytopenia, and acute kidney injury (elevated creatinine). \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic uraemic syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents following a diarrhoeal illness, often caused by toxin-producing bacteria such as \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E O157:H7. The recent history of food poisoning strongly supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisseminated intravascular coagulation\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bleeding, shock and multiple organ dysfunction. It usually occurs secondary to infection or malignancy, neither of which are evident here. Additionally, coagulation studies would be abnormal in DIC.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune thrombocytopaenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E is also characterised by isolated thrombocytopenia, classically following viral infection in children. However, it is considered a diagnosis of exclusion, and would not account for the anaemia or renal dysfunction seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E requires more severely elevated blood pressure (typically \u0026gt;180/120 mmHg) and would not explain the haematological abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHenoch-Sch\u00f6nlein purpura\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with palpable purpura, arthritis, abdominal pain and renal involvement. While it can cause hypertension and renal dysfunction (with haematuria or proteinuria on urine dipstick), it would not explain the haematological findings of this case. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemolytic uraemic syndrome classically presents with microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia and acute kidney injury following a diarrhoeal illness.","Recent food poisoning with subsequent lethargy, pallor and hypertension should raise suspicion for haemolytic uraemic syndrome in children.","Normal coagulation studies help differentiate haemolytic uraemic syndrome from disseminated intravascular coagulation."],"references":["Fakhouri et al. Haemolytic uraemic syndrome. Lancet. 2017 Aug 12;390(10095):681-696.","Kausman, J (2013).\u00a0517 Haemolytic uraemic syndrome.\u00a0Accessed at:\u00a0https://www.rch.org.au/nephrology/protocols/517_Haemolytic_Uraemic_Syndrome/","Cody EM, Dixon BP. Hemolytic Uremic Syndrome. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2019 Feb;66(1):235-246."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75756"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"76"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75756"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-17T19:53:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-17T19:53:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"76"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questio